  abstract = {{$<$}p{$>$} We estimate the blank carbon mass over the course of a typical Ramped PyrOx (RPO) analysis (150–1000°C; 5°C×min \textsuperscript{–1} ) to be (3.7±0.6) μg C with an Fm value of 0.555±0.042 and a δ \textsuperscript{13} C value of (–29.0±0.1) ‰ VPDB. Additionally, we provide equations for RPO Fm and δ \textsuperscript{13} C blank corrections, including associated error propagation. By comparing RPO mass-weighted mean and independently measured bulk δ \textsuperscript{13} C values for a compilation of environmental samples and standard reference materials (SRMs), we observe a small yet consistent \textsuperscript{13} C depletion within the RPO instrument (mean–bulk: μ=–0.8‰; ±1σ=0.9‰; {$<$}italic{$>$}n{$<$}/italic{$>$} =66). In contrast, because they are fractionation-corrected by definition, mass-weighted mean Fm values accurately match bulk measurements (mean–bulk: μ=0.005; ±1σ=0.014; {$<$}italic{$>$}n{$<$}/italic{$>$} =36). Lastly, we show there exists no significant intra-sample δ \textsuperscript{13} C variability across carbonate SRM peaks, indicating minimal mass-dependent kinetic isotope fractionation during RPO analysis. These data are best explained by a difference in activation energy between \textsuperscript{13} C- and \textsuperscript{12} C-containing compounds ( \textsuperscript{13–12} {$<$}italic{$>$}∆E{$<$}/italic{$>$} ) of 0.3–1.8 J×mol \textsuperscript{–1} , indicating that blank and mass-balance corrected RPO δ \textsuperscript{13} C values accurately retain carbon source isotope signals to within 1–2‰. {$<$}/p{$>$}},
